results.notes:
Clustered frozen/mature fruiting on hardwood.
Three fused fruits approximately 5ft up host tree. Oak, elm and Maple dominant here.
The youngest cap(in center) showing rubbery, tan, blotchy, aereolate nature. Mature caps heavily are scaly, cracked/aereolate. Stipes are thick and centrally attached and vertically striated(just like mature H. ulmarius). Gills are broadly attached. Not decurrent.
Spore Print: Whitish tan.
The fact that these fruits are fruiting in a clustered nature and have far smaller stature makes confident identification as Hypsizygus tessulatus over H. ulmarius. H. ulmarius is far larger annd anlways fruits singularly. Also, the youngest fruiting body in this collection with rubbery grayish tan blotchy cap is exemplar for young tessulatus.
Harvested a single specimen and dehydrated thoroughly for herbarium collection/genetic record.

Fruitbodies appeared after 2 weeks of rains and temps ranging from subfreezing to 50F.

What say you? Is this a non-bluing psilocybe, or a hypholoma, or something else?

results.notes:
On decaying wood; At first I thought hardwood, probably beech. But a subsequent examination of the habitat suggests the wood may be hemlock.
Cap color ranged from tan, to brown, to dark gray-brown. I looked at spores from pale ones and dark ones and there is no difference. All growing on the same large decaying log.
Spores amyloid, 5.5-7 × 2.5-3.5; lengths variable one fruit body having spores with maximum length exceeding 7 microns and a significant percentage around 7; another fruit body with almost all lengths not exceeding 6 microns. Photos show spores from (respectively) pale and dark capped examples.
The spores are small, but larger than what is reported on Mycoquebec or Mushroom Expert for M. semivestipes.
Another collection of similar mushrooms, but with smaller spores, found on the same day same location; on a different log at slightly higher elevation, obs 510416.
